Import Pre-Built Wiki ESA Model

Explicit Semantic Analysis (ESA) is an unsupervised algorithm for feature extraction of explicit features based on an existing knowledge base. ESA improves text document categorization by calculating semantic relatedness (how similar in meaning two words or pieces of text are to each other) between the documents and a set of topics that are explicitly defined and described by humans.

This pre-built ESA model is based on millions of Wikipedia articles reduced to about 161,000 topics. The model was built under database version 19c using the July 1, 2021 Wikipedia dump.

The Oracle Machine Learning for SQL functionESA, Oracle Machine Learning for Python function oml.esa and Oracle Machine Learning for R function ore.odmESA extract text-based features from a corpus of documents and performs document similarity comparisons. In this notebook, we'll import the wiki ESA model to Autonomous Database for use with the OML template notebook examples:

  • OML4SQL Feature Extraction ESA Wiki Model
  • OML4Py Feature Extraction ESA Wiki Model
  • OML4R Feature Extraction ESA Wiki Model

- **Option 2**: Use the model dump file already saved in the public Object Storage bucket provided in this example.

paragraphs.title: Required Grants

msg.data:
Copy the model dump file from the Object Storage Bucket to the Autonomous Database data pump directory, and then import the model to the database. In SQL Developer, the OML ADMIN must grant the OML user read and write access to the data pump directory. The OML user also requires sevaral text policy grants to work with the model.

In this example, the OML user is OMLUSER.

GRANT read, write ON DIRECTORY DATA_PUMP_DIR TO OMLUSER;
GRANT EXECUTE ON CTXSYS.CTX_DDL TO OMLUSER;
GRANT EXECUTE ON CTXSYS.CTX_OUTPUT TO OMLUSER;
GRANT EXECUTE ON CTXSYS.CTX_THES TO OMLUSER;

paragraphs.title: Object Storage
paragraphs.text:
%md
_________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________
Oracle Autonomous Database provides the `DBMS_CLOUD` package. This enables the transfer of objects between Autonomous Database and Object Storage. Object Storage stores data as objects within buckets, or containers, and are identified with an URI having the following format:

    https://objectstorage.region.oraclecloud.com/v1/tenantname/bucketname/objectname

This example is using a public bucket, but access to the objects stored within buckets is protected for non-public buckets. To access objects in a non-public bucket, one must to provide identification information stored into a credential object. Refer to the ADB User's Guide more information on the `DBMS_CLOUD` package and credentials.

paragraphs.title: Copy the model dump file from Object Storage to the Autonomous Database data pump directory
paragraphs.text:
%md
____________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________
Use the `DBMS_CLOUD.GET_OBJECT` procedure to copy the model dump file to the data pump directory. In this example, the *credential_name* parameter is set to NULL because the bucket is public. For non-public buckets, a credential name must be provided, and can be created using the `CREATE_CREDENTIAL` procedure. The *object_uri* parameter provides the model dump file's URI in the Object Storage bucket, and the *directory_name* parameter indicates we want to copy the object to the data pump directory.

For more information on the `CREATE_CREDENTIAL` procedure, refer to the Autonomous Database User's Guide:

#### [CREATE_CREDENTIAL Procedure](https://docs.oracle.com/en/cloud/paas/autonomous-database/adbsa/dbms-cloud-subprograms.html#GUID-742FC365-AA09-48A8-922C-1987795CF36A)

paragraphs.title: Import the model
paragraphs.text:
%md

The `DBMS_DATA_MINING` package provides the `DBMS_DATA_MINING.IMPORT_MODEL` function to import a model to the database. 

We import the model, first dropping it if it already exists.  For the model import, pass the model dump file name to the *filename* parameter. Provide the name of the directory containing the file, the data pump directory, to the *directory* parameter. Remap the tablespace used in the development database, DMUSER, to the current user's tablespace, OMLUSER.
